article.description: Yolanda Griffith had 21 points and eight rebounds and Ticha Penicheiro added a surprising 15 points in the Monarchs' 87-66 victory over the Storm.
article.headline: Griffith, Penicheiro power Monarchs past Storm
article.linkText: Griffith, Penicheiro power Monarchs past Storm
article.story: SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Although Ticha Penicheiro gets the scoring itch only a few times every season, the Sacramento Monarchs are a dominant team when she scratches it. Yolanda Griffith had 21 points and eight rebounds and Penicheiro added a surprising 15 points in the Sacramento's 87-66 victory over the Seattle Storm on Wednesday night. Nicole Powell and rookie Scholanda Dorrell scored 12 points apiece for the Monarchs, who have won three of their first four to open defense of their WNBA title. The Monarchs grabbed this one early, taking a 20-point lead in the first half and cruising past their longtime Seattle rivals, the 2004 league champs. The Monarchs' perceived lack of a go-to scorer didn't show against the Storm. Griffith was resourceful in the post, while Sacramento repeatedly penetrated the lane -- and got an uncharacteristic burst from Penicheiro, the WNBA's career assists leader who's well-known for her reluctance to shoot. If Griffith knew any way to coax these games from her longtime teammate more often, she would have done it years ago. "Nobody respects Ticha offensively, but when she's aggressive, she makes everything easier for everybody out there," said Griffith, who got an ovation for diving over the scorers' table in pursuit of a loose ball in the third quarter. "It's not four-on-five when she's aggressive like that. It's five-on-five. Everybody is always telling her she's got to play like this all the time, but I don't know what it is," she said. Sacramento never trailed after the opening basket, making an 18-5 run and following it up with a 16-6 surge to a 36-20 lead early in the second quarter. Penicheiro went 6-for-7 in the first half -- even with her last name misspelled on the back of her jersey -- and hit a driving layup with 3.1 seconds left to put the Monarchs up 49-29 at halftime. "I was pleased with the way we played," Penicheiro said, smiling but offering no explanation for her big game. "They're no scrubs. They're one of the best teams in the league, and we got going from the jump." Lauren Jackson had 20 points and eight rebounds for the Storm in her first game since scoring a career-high 35 against Phoenix last week. Betty Lennox scored 18 points, including the 2,000th of her career, but Sue Bird was held to six points on 2-of-9 shooting and one assist by Sacramento's hard-nosed defense. "When things went bad, they went really bad, and we never snapped out of it," Bird said. "If you know our team, you know that's not normal for us. But that's what Sacramento does. They can take you out of your game." Sacramento Kings forward Ron Artest sat courtside with two of his children, perhaps to get a look at Monarchs coach John Whisenant, who's in the running to be Artest's next coach with the Kings. Whisenant, who never played or coached in the NBA, interviewed for the job last week and was thought to be the Maloof brothers' favorite candidate. But Memphis assistant Eric Musselman was scheduled to get a second interview with the Kings' top brass Wednesday night in Las Vegas. Whisenant, whose Monarchs host San Antonio on Friday night, said he has no plans to travel to the Palms casino any time soon. "I'm worried about the Monarchs," Whisenant said. "The Monarchs are my job, and that's all I'm concentrating on. ... I'm focused only on the Monarchs, and I have no comment on [the Kings]. I'm focusing on the court I have some control over."
